<body>

<div class="slide" style="page-break-before: auto; text-align: center; margin-top: 2in;">
  <h1>DISASTER RESPONSE &amp; RESCUE NAVIGATION SYSTEM</h1>
  <p><b>A Graph-Based Emergency Route Planning System Using DSA</b></p>
  <p style="margin-top: 1in; font-size: 16pt;">
    Submitted By: Bhavyaswi (Roll No: 17) &amp; Teammate (Teja)<br>
    Department of Computer Science and Engineering<br>
    Lovely Professional University, Punjab, India<br>
    Academic Year: 2025 - 2026
  </p>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>01. OVERVIEW &amp; MOTIVATION</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Disaster management is critical for saving lives during floods, cyclones, and landslides.</li>
    <li>Emergency routing during the initial "Golden Hours" determines victim survival rates.</li>
    <li>Conventional GPS navigation engines optimize strictly for distance or traffic congestion.</li>
    <li>They do not account for safety levels, road hazards, or emergency resource locations.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>02. PROBLEM STATEMENT</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Natural disasters cause severe transport blockages, cutting off critical road links.</li>
    <li>Rescue coordinators lack visibility on road passability and dynamic safety levels.</li>
    <li>No existing open-source tool integrates routing with local hospital bed and shelter capacities.</li>
    <li>C++ routing binaries are blocked in serverless cloud environments like Vercel.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>03. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE</h1>
  <ul>
    <li><b>Interactive Map Canvas:</b> Developed with HTML5, CSS3, Vanilla JS, and Leaflet.js maps.</li>
    <li><b>Dual-Engine Backend:</b> High-performance compiled C++ core for local operations.</li>
    <li><b>Cloud JS Fallback:</b> Native JavaScript DSA engine (dsaEngine.js) running on Vercel serverless nodes.</li>
    <li><b>Database Layer:</b> Predefined CSV files loading cities, roads, and emergency resources.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>04. GRAPH MODELING</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Road network represented as a mathematical graph G = (V, E).</li>
    <li>Includes 41 major Indian cities (Vertices) and 69 connecting highways (Edges).</li>
    <li>Adjacency List configuration reduces memory overhead for sparse networks.</li>
    <li>Danger ratings (1-5) scale dynamically on adjacent road links when disasters are triggered.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>05. DYNAMIC DIJKSTRA PATHFINDING</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Computes optimal path based on physical distance and road hazard safety ratings.</li>
    <li>Min-Priority Queue (Min-Heap) used to select the lowest cost node in O(log V) time.</li>
    <li><b>Safety Weight Formula:</b> Edge Cost = Distance * (1.0 + (Danger Level - 1) * 0.3).</li>
    <li>Forces pathfinders to calculate alternative detours around active disaster areas.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>06. HEURISTIC A* SEARCH</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Evaluates nodes based on f(n) = g(n) + h(n) to focus the pathfinding search space.</li>
    <li>Heuristic h(n) uses the Haversine formula to compute great-circle distance on a sphere.</li>
    <li>Latitudes and longitudes of all 41 cities are loaded from coordinate database.</li>
    <li>Reduces visited nodes by up to 56% compared to Dijkstra's algorithm.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>07. BFS &amp; DFS GRAPH TRAVERSALS</h1>
  <ul>
    <li><b>Breadth-First Search (BFS):</b> Level-by-level traversal using Queue to analyze network hops.</li>
    <li><b>Depth-First Search (DFS):</b> Recursive traversal using Stack to verify topological connectivity.</li>
    <li>Helps dispatchers identify all cities directly reachable from an emergency camp.</li>
    <li>Determinism ensured by sorting adjacent nodes alphabetically during exploration.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>08. PERFORMANCE BENCHMARKS</h1>
  <ul>
    <li><b>Dijkstra (Safe):</b> 2203.4 km distance | 32 nodes expanded | 0.14 ms execution time</li>
    <li><b>A* (Haversine):</b> 2203.4 km distance | 14 nodes expanded | 0.08 ms execution time</li>
    <li><b>BFS (Hops):</b> 2412.0 km distance | 38 nodes expanded | 0.18 ms execution time</li>
    <li><b>DFS (Depth):</b> 4102.8 km distance | 41 nodes expanded | 0.24 ms execution time</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>09. EMERGENCY RESOURCE COORDINATION</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>The system tracks critical resources along the calculated path.</li>
    <li>Hospitals: Returns available emergency bed counts and contact details.</li>
    <li>Shelters: Lists emergency shelter capacities and occupancies for relief planning.</li>
    <li>Rescue Teams: Details nearby dispatch groups specialized in water, medical, or fire rescues.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="slide">
  <h1>10. CONCLUSION &amp; FUTURE SCOPE</h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Successfully integrated C++ and JS fallbacks to solve emergency routing in serverless clouds.</li>
    <li><b>Future Work:</b> Integrate live traffic feeds and weather forecast APIs.</li>
    <li><b>Offline Routing:</b> Deploy Progressive Web Apps (PWA) with radio mesh networking.</li>
    <li><b>Predictive Models:</b> ML models predicting road blockage risk using rain forecasts.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

</body>
